Project: TMDb Movie Data Analysis¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

In this project, we will be analyzing data associated with TMDb Movie data set that contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue.

In particular, we will be interested to answer the following question :

  1. Which genres are most popular? have high bugests? have high revenues?
  2. Which genres are most popular from year to year? have highest bugest from year to year? have highest revenue from year to year?

  3. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?

    To start, we wil import the packages we need for this analysis :

First impression¶

  • There is one duplicated row, it will be droped.

  • There are columns in the dataset, which are not important to the intended analysis and therefore will be removed. This includes:

    • imdb_id
    • cast
    • homepage
    • director
    • overview
    • release_date
    • tagline
    • keywords
    • production_companies

  • Columns, like genres, contains some nan values (23 nan value) : rows with nan values represent only 0.2% , so it will be removed.

  • df.describe() indicates that many columns, especially budget and revenue, contain many "0" in their columns. In order to provide a proper analysis, the columns budget_adj, revenue_adj, budget, revenue and runtime will change its "0" values into its mean value.

  • genres column seems to contain several values, which are seperated by an "|". They need to be cleaned in order to provide a proper dataset for the intended analysis.

def myBarPlot(df, col, unit=None) :
    '''
    This function will plot col value for each genre unsing seaborn.barplot
    Inputs :
     - df : pandas DataFrame
     - col : column name, type string 
    '''
    # change figure size
    plt.figure(figsize = [20, 10])
    # change color palette
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    # sort genres using col value by descending
    genres_order = df.sort_values(col, ascending=False).index
    # define x and y for barplot
    x = df.index
    y = df[col]
    # plot x and y using seaborn.barplot
    sb.barplot(x, y, color=base_color, order=genres_order)
    # add x label and format it
    plt.xlabel('Genres', fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    # add y label and format it, add unit if exist
    plt.ylabel(f'{col}({unit})'.title() if unit else col.title() , fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    # add title and format it
    plt.title(f'Ranking Genres by {col}'.title(), fontsize=14, weight='bold')
    # rotate x ticks by 45°
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)

def myCountPlot(serie, var) :
    '''
    This function will plot numder of times each genre takes the first place for each year, 
    ranking by var value,
    using seabor.countplot() function
    Inputs :
     - serie : pandas serie contains for each genre, the number of times takes the fisrt place each year based on var value
     - var : type string 
    '''
    # change figure size
    plt.figure(figsize = [20, 10])
    # add y grid
    plt.grid(axis='y')
    # change color palette
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    # sort genres using col value by descending
    genres_order = serie.value_counts().index
    # plot using seaborn.barplot
    sb.countplot(x=serie, color=base_color, order=genres_order)
    # add x label and format it
    plt.xlabel('Genres', fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    # add y label and format it
    plt.ylabel('Number of Times' , fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    # add title and format it
    plt.title(f'Ranking Genres by yearly {col}'.title(), fontsize=14, weight='bold')
    # rotate x ticks by 45°
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)

def myScatterPlot(df, xVar, yVar, xUnit=None, yUnit=None) :
    '''
    This function will plot relationship between xVar and yVar
    Inputs :
     - df : pandas DataFrame
     - xVar : fisrt column name, type string
     - yVar : second column name, type string
     - xUnit : unit of xVar, type string, by default None
     - yUnit : unit of yVar, type string, by default None 
    '''
    # change figsize
    plt.figure(figsize = [14.70, 8.27])
    # Scatter plot to check correlation between xVar and yVar
    sb.regplot(data=df, x=xVar, y=yVar, truncate=False);
    # add x label and format it, add unit if exist
    plt.xlabel(f'{xVar}({xUnit})'.title() if xUnit else xVar.title(), fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    # add y label and format it, add unit if exist
    plt.ylabel(f'{yVar}({yUnit})'.title() if yUnit else yVar.title(), fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    # add title and format it
    plt.title(f'Relationship between {xVar} and {yVar}'.title(), fontsize=14, weight='bold')

Conclusions¶

Question 1: from 1960 to 2015, Adventure movies are the most popular and have the highest revenue and budget. In last place, we find Foreign and Documentary as least popular and with lowest revenue and budget.

Question 2: From year to year, Adventure genre appears 14 times as the yearly most popular, 12 times with yearly highest budget, and 16 times with yearly highest revenue.

Question 3: Correlation table and scatter plots show that revenue variable of Top 100 movies with highest revenue has moderate correlation with vote_count and weak correlation with popurality, budget, vote_average and runtime. Comparing the mean value of all movies, Top 100 movies with highest revenue are more popular, have higher budget, longer and with higher vote average(6.9).

All results are limited to the underlying data set and as no advaned statistics were performed, the results can only be treated as indicators and are not generalizable. Furthermore, one has to consider that many entries in the dataset have been removed due to missing data
